<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126633936-52db4f92-8b2b-4661-8d9c-7bf787cdeb90.png" alt="image" /></p>

<h3 id="dropping">Dropping</h3>
<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126633984-262e3862-76d3-4652-bc95-98b4b90332ad.png" alt="image" /></p>

<h3 id="yaw">Yaw</h3>
<p>Yaw is the motion of the drone in the xy plane, or the horizontal plane as shown in the previous figure. The opposite kind of pair of propellers will create reaction movements. If the sum of all the movements of each propeller is equal to each other, then there is no yaw motion. But if there is difference movements between any pair of propellers, there will be yaw motion, and the drone will move, as shown in the following figure:
<img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126634068-327c6d35-0b3b-4da8-beeb-0a5b8bd12559.png" alt="image" />
<img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126634226-949aae09-6bda-4fab-b780-ff69c6cf9b78.png" alt="image" /></p>

<h3 id="pitch-and-roll">Pitch and roll</h3>
<p>The pitch is the rotation of the drone in the Y direction, while the rotation along the X direction is known as roll or vice versa, depending on the front of the drone. This will happen if one pair of opposite propellers provide, thrust more than the other two propellers.</p>

<h2 id="ch1-background-concept">Ch1. Background concept</h2>
<p><a href="https://onofflinkinc.slack.com/files/UHPPRAQD7/F028EF6JBHD/arduinoesp8266drone.pdf">packt_book</a></p>

<p>$\displaystyle \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}$  <img src="https://render.githubusercontent.com/render/math?math=x_{1,2} = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2b}" /></p>

<p><a href="https://www.mathcha.io/editor">math-writing</a></p>

<p>\begin{equation<em>}
\left(\frac{xdx}{dy} -\frac{ydy}{dx}\right)^{2} \ ,\ [\vec{F} =m\vec{a}] \ ,\ \left| \frac{a}{b}\right| \ \left\Vert \frac{a}{b}\right\Vert \ \left&lt; \frac{a}{b}\right&gt; \left{\sqrt{a+\sqrt{a+\sqrt{a}}}\rightarrow \infty \right}
\end{equation</em>}</p>

<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126624695-d4f7211d-73aa-4bb4-9295-9c63396e86f7.png" alt="image" /></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>If P is the payload capacity of your drone (how much your drone can lift. Iâ€™ll explain how
you can find it), M is the number of motors, W is the weight of the drone itself, and H is the
hover throttle % (will be explained later). Then, our thrust of the motors T will be as
follows:</p>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126624917-601fbb85-7077-40ba-ae4d-a2d106c0df30.png" alt="image" /></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The droneâ€™s payload capacity can be found with the following equation:</p>
</blockquote>

<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42961200/126625107-73fa86fe-4af3-4558-b7ca-9cf06f77af22.png" alt="image" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>FCs on the market</li>
</ul>

